Intrusion Detection System (IDS)
Intrusion detection systems (IDSs) can be classified as follows:
Host-based IDS: 
Monitors the characteristics of a single host and the events occurring within that host for 
suspicious activity. This allows host-based IDSs to determine exactly which processes and 
user accounts are involved in a particular attack on the OS. 
Furthermore, unlike network-based IDSs, host-based IDSs can see the intended outcome 
of an attempted attack, because they can directly access and monitor the data files and 
system processes usually targeted by attacks.
Network-based IDS: 
Monitors network traffic for particular network segments or devices and analyzes 
network, transport, and application protocols to identify suspicious activity.
